{{Culture of Spain}}
In 2018, two firms in [[Spain]] ranked among the world's biggest [[book publisher|publishers of books]] in terms of revenue: [[Grupo Planeta]] and [[Grupo Santillana]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/20180917/78036-pearson-is-still-the-world-s-largest-publisher.html |title= The World's 54 Largest Publishers, 2018 |date= 14 September 2018 |work=[[Publishers Weekly]] |location=US |volume=265 |number= 38 }}</ref>{{refn|group=nb|The same two also topped the list in 2016 in 2017.<ref>{{citation |work=Publishers Weekly |location=US |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/international/international-book-news/article/71268-the-world-s-52-largest-book-publishers-2016.html |title=World's 52 Largest Book Publishers, 2016 |date= 26 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{citation |work=Publishers Weekly |location=US |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/international/international-book-news/article/74505-the-world-s-50-largest-publishers-2017.html |title=World's 54 Largest Publishers, 2017 |date= 25 August 2017}}</ref>}} In 2013, there were 524,213 titles [[:wikt:in print|in print]] in Spain, including 76,434 new titles.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.internationalpublishers.org/images/reports/2014/ipa-country-report-spain-book-market.pdf |title=Spanish book market data |work=IPA Country Report |publisher=[[International Publishers Association]] |author=Federación de Gremios de Editores de España |year=2014 }}</ref>

==History==
{{see also|Global spread of the printing press#Spain}}

"The first Spanish [[printing press|press]] was set up in 1473 at [[Valencia]], where the German trading company of Ravensburg had an important base.... Publishing flourished in the early period at [[Barcelona]], [[Burgos]], [[Zaragoza]], [[Seville]], and the university towns of [[Salamanca]] and [[Alcalá de Henares]]."<ref name=Britannica>{{cite web |work=[[Britannica.com]] |url= https://www.britannica.com/topic/publishing |title=History of Publishing |accessdate= 20 November 2017 }}</ref> The Instituto Nacional del Libro Español (National Book Institute) formed in 1941.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://datos.bne.es/entidad/XX141541.html |title=Instituto Nacional del Libro Español |language=es |work=Datos.bne.es |publisher= [[Biblioteca Nacional de España]] |accessdate= 20 November 2017 }}</ref> As of 2004 Spain had some 2,000+ book publishers in the private sector, including {{illm|Prensa Española|es}}, and [[PRISA|Prisa]].{{sfn|De Mateo|2004}} As of 2013 there were 809 publishing enterprises.

The [[United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]] designated [[Madrid]] the 2001 [[World Book Capital]].

